'''Bea Arthur''' (born '''Bernice Frankel'''; [[May 13]], [[1920s|1922]] &ndash; [[April 25]], [[2009]]) was an [[Wikipedia:United States|American]] [[Wikipedia:Actor|actress]] known for her deep voice and sharp delivery of [[Wikipedia:Comedy|comedic]] lines who gained fame acting on [[Wikipedia:Broadway theatre|Broadway]], in [[Wikipedia:Television program|television]], and in [[Wikipedia:Film|films]] throughout her long career. One highlight of her career, [[Wikipedia:Maude (TV series)|''Maude'']], was a sitcom of her own which ran for six successful seasons.

In [[1978]], Arthur was invited to appear on ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]'', a holiday-themed [[Wikipedia:Variety show|variety show]] set in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe that was attempting to capitalize off of the success of the wildly popular film of the previous year, [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']]. Arthur portrayed [[Ackmena/Legends|Ackmena]], a gruff [[Bartender/Legends|bartender]] at the [[Mos Eisley/Legends|Mos Eisley]] [[Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina/Legends|Cantina]] whose rowdy patrons refused to obey a [[Planet/Legends|planet]]-wide curfew imposed by the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]]. Ackmena resorted to singing the song "[[Goodnight, But Not Goodbye/Legends|Goodnight, But Not Goodbye]]," which caused them to waltz out the door.

Arthur found further success on television when she played the pragmatic [[Wikipedia:Dorothy Zbornak|Dorothy Zbornak]] on the 1980s sitcom [[Wikipedia:The Golden Girls|''The Golden Girls'']], a very popular show throughout its seven year run. After falling ill from [[Wikipedia:Cancer|cancer]], Arthur passed away in her home in [[2009]]. She was remembered fondly by friends, family, and the Broadway community.

==Biography==
===''The Star Wars Holiday Special''===
{{Quote|It was a wonderful time, but I had no idea it was even a part of the whole ''Star Wars'' thing.''"<br />"''Well, that song ''was'' great.''"<br />"''Well, thanks. It's odd. I've gotten so many letters and requests for autographed photos from that thing. I just remember singing to bunch of people with funny heads.|Bea Arthur|<ref name="mercury">{{WebCite|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/film/the-bea-arthur-interview/Content?oid=35024|text=The Bea Arthur Interview|author=Gardner, Will|date=2005-10-13|work=[[Wikipedia:Portland Mercury|Portland Mercury]]|archivedate=20200409235503}}</ref>}}
[[File:Justonemoreroundfriend.jpg|thumb|right|Arthur sang to a group of intoxicated aliens in ''The Star Wars Holiday Special''.]]
As the Emmy-winning lead of one of television's most popular shows, Arthur was a star.<ref name="lifetime4">{{YouTube|video=2DF1U8g034g|text=Bea Arthur Pt 4/5|channel=@dingdong131|name=dingdong131|nobackup=1}}</ref> In [[1978]], she was invited by<ref name="mercury" /> [[Ken Welch|Ken]] and [[Mitzie Welch]],<ref name="Comedy Hour">{{WebCite|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2008/12/star_wars_special200812|text=The Han Solo Comedy Hour!|author=DiGiacomo, Frank|date=2008-12-22|work=[[Wikipedia:Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|archivedate=20200113025908}}</ref> the composers of a song called "[[Goodnight, But Not Goodbye/Legends|Goodnight, But Not Goodbye]]," to sing it on a television program called ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''.<ref name="mercury" /> [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] had been a wildly successful film released the previous year,<ref name="eod">''[[Empire of Dreams: The Story of the Star Wars Trilogy]]''</ref> and a holiday-themed variety show was being produced to capitalize off of its success.<ref name="filmfax">{{SWArchive|url=movies/saga/20081117.html|text=Holiday Special: Script and Directors}} (''Filmfax'' magazine #69/70)</ref> Arthur played the role of [[Ackmena/Legends|Ackmena]], a gruff and assertive [[Bartender/Legends|bartender]] working the night shift at the [[Mos Eisley/Legends|Mos Eisley]] [[Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina/Legends|Cantina]], who was forced to close down the [[Cantina/Legends|bar]] after the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] imposed a [[Planet/Legends|planet]]-wide curfew. When the patrons refused to leave, she resorted to singing "Goodnight, But Not Goodbye," which prompted everyone present to waltz out the door.<ref name="holiday special">''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''</ref>

Arthur's scene proved to be a lengthy shoot,<ref name="Comedy Hour" /> spanning twenty-four hours,<ref name="Starlog">Millar, Natalie. [[Starlog (magazine)|''Starlog'']] Number 19, [[February]] [[1979]]: "'Star Wars' Invades TV"</ref> but she nevertheless enjoyed working on the special, even though she was unaware that it was part of the larger ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise. Years later, she would recall singing to a group of people with funny heads,<ref name="mercury" /> as the various cantina patrons had been [[Alien/Legends|aliens]] from throughout the ''Star Wars'' [[The galaxy/Legends|galaxy]].<ref name="holiday special" /> The special itself received good reviews at the time,<ref>{{WebCite|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/star-wars-holiday-special-review-1978-tv-show-749584|text='The Star Wars Holiday Special': THR's 1978 Review|author=THR Staff|date=2014-11-17|work=[[Wikipedia:The Hollywood Reporter|The Hollywood Reporter]]|archivedate=20190507122507}}</ref> but ultimately came to be almost universally panned by later reviewers.<ref name="multimedia">{{WebCite|url=http://starwarsholidayspecial.com/multimedia.htm|text=Holiday Special Multimedia|work=[http://www.starwarsholidayspecial.com StarWarsHolidaySpecial.com]|archivedate=20180827065634}}</ref><ref name="panned">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/me2/9.html|text=Star Wars: Episode II &#124; Part 9: Bucket Head}}</ref><ref name="farce1">{{WebCite|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-nov-16-ca-starwars16-story.html|text=May the farce be with you|author=Liebenson, Donald|date=2008-11-16|work=[[Wikipedia:Los Angeles Times|Los Angeles Times]]|archivedate=20191115073321}}</ref><ref name="Jawa">{{InsiderCite|94|Jawa's Corner}}</ref> Arthur's musical performance has been cited as one of its high points,<ref name="Bad Feeling">{{InsiderCite|106|I Have a Bad Feeling About This!}}</ref> despite being considered just as bizarre as the rest of the production.<ref name="farce1" /><ref name="Comedy Hour" /> Arthur's role led to scores of letters and requests for autographed photos from ''Star Wars'' fans throughout the proceeding years.<ref name="mercury" />

===Death===
{{Quote|All in all, I've had a damn good life.|Bea Arthur|<ref name="lifetime" />}}
After becoming ill from [[Wikipedia:Cancer|cancer]], she passed away at her home on [[April 25]], [[2009]],<ref name="NY Times" /><ref name="obituary2">{{WebCite|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/TV/04/25/bea.arthur.obit/index.html|text=Two-time Emmy Award winner Bea Arthur dead at 86|date=2009-04-27|work=[[Wikipedia:CNN International|CNN International]]|archivedate=20191123001142}}</ref> and her body was [[Wikipedia:Cremation|cremated]].<ref name="cremated">{{WebCite|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/36348603/bea-arthur|text=Bea Arthur|author=Hufford, Bob|date=2009-04-25|work=[[Wikipedia:Find a Grave|Find a Grave]]|archivedate=20191227110234}}</ref> Arthur was remembered fondly by many of her friends and co-stars, including Angela Lansbury, Betty White, and [[Wikipedia:Adrienne Barbeau|Adrienne Barbeau]],<ref name="murdershewrote">{{WebCite|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/2009/04/73215|text=Angela Lansbury 'Deeply Saddened' By Bea Arthur's Passing|date=2009-04-25|work=[[Wikipedia:Entertainment Tonight|ETonline]]|archivedate=20100818083854}}</ref><ref name="tribute">{{WebCite|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/beatrice-arthur-tribute-1005473|text=Friends and Colleagues Remember Beatrice Arthur|author=Eng, Joyce|date=2009-04-27|work=[[Wikipedia:TV Guide|TV Guide]]|archivedate=20190929072227}}</ref> and the Broadway community paid tribute to her life by dimming the [[Wikipedia:Marquee (sign)|marquees]] of New York City's Broadway theatre district for one minute on [[April 28]], 2009.<ref name="tribute2">{{WebCite|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/2009/04/73316|text=Broadway Plans Tribute To Bea Arthur|date=2009-04-28|work=[[Wikipedia:Entertainment Tonight|ETonline]]|archivedate=20100820073750}}</ref>

